Analysis of the usage rate of the online-to-offline (O2O) pickup order feature on a certain e-commerce website¶

A certain online e-commerce website has launched the "online-to-offline pickup order" feature. We aim to understand the current usage status and influencing factors of this feature, as well as identify a key list of customers that could help increase the usage rate of this feature.

Clean and organize data according to business rules.¶

In [127]:
# Filter out data that meets the assessment rules
df = df[df['Warehouse'].isin (['Warehouse_A','Warehouse_B'])]
df = df.drop_duplicates(['Outbound plan number'])

# delete the useless characters
df['Order Time'] = df['Order Time'].apply(lambda x: x[:19])
# transform the data type
df['Order Time'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Order Time'])

# the business rule mark the Order type 1,4,5,6 as online way, others is offline way.
df['Order type'].replace({1:'online', 2:'offline', 3:'offline', 4:'online', 5:'online', 6:'online'}, inplace = True)

Explore the proportion of Online Orders to Total Orders¶

In [119]:
# Total orders vs. Online orders Pie Chart
total_orders = df['Outbound plan number'].count()
online_orders = df[df['Order type'] == 'online']['Outbound plan number'].count()
offline_orders = total_orders - online_orders

# Data for pie chart
labels = 'Online Orders', 'Offline Orders'
sizes = [online_orders, offline_orders]
colors = ['lightcoral', 'lightskyblue']
explode = (0.1, 0)  # explode 1st slice

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(4, 4))
plt.pie(sizes, explode=explode, labels=labels, colors=colors, autopct='%1.1f%%', shadow=True, startangle=140)
plt.title('Proportion of Online Orders to Total Orders')
plt.axis('equal')
plt.show()

Explore the relationship between product categories and online ordering rates.¶

In [136]:
df_product_analyst = df

df_product_analyst['Online Order'] = df_product_analyst['Order type'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x == 'online' else 0)
df_product_analyst['Offline Order'] = df_product_analyst['Order type'].apply(lambda x: 0 if x == 'offline' else 1)

# Group by product category, calculate the total number of orders, the number of online orders, and the number of offline orders.
grouped = df_product_analyst.groupby('Product name').agg(
    Total_Orders=pd.NamedAgg(column='Order type', aggfunc='count'),
    Online_Orders=pd.NamedAgg(column='Online Order', aggfunc='sum'),
    Offline_Orders=pd.NamedAgg(column='Offline Order', aggfunc='sum')
).reset_index()
grouped.sort_values(by='Offline_Orders', ascending=False, inplace=True)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(30, 18))
ind = np.arange(len(grouped))
width = 0.35

p1 = ax.bar(ind, grouped['Online_Orders'], width, label='Online Orders', color='skyblue')
p2 = ax.bar(ind, grouped['Offline_Orders'], width, bottom=grouped['Online_Orders'], label='Offline Orders', color='lightgrey')

ax.set_title('Total and Online Orders by Product Category')
ax.set_xlabel('Product Category')
ax.set_ylabel('Number of Orders')
ax.set_xticks(ind)
ax.set_xticklabels(grouped['Product name'], rotation=45)
ax.legend()

plt.show()

We can see the main goods of the relevant warehouse and the proportion of order methods for their pick-up orders. However, it appears that the category of goods does not affect the customers' ordering methods.

Explore the relationship between order timing and online ordering rates.¶

In [147]:
df_line_chart = df.set_index('Order Time')

df_line_chart['hour'] = df_line_chart.index.hour

hourly_data = df_line_chart.groupby('hour').agg(
    Total_Orders=('Order type', 'count'),
    Online_Orders=('Online Order', 'sum')
)


hourly_data['Online Order Rate'] = hourly_data['Online_Orders'] / hourly_data['Total_Orders']


fig, ax1 = plt.subplots()


color = 'tab:red'
ax1.set_xlabel('Hour of Day')
ax1.set_ylabel('Number of Orders', color=color)
ax1.plot(hourly_data.index, hourly_data['Total_Orders'], color=color, label='Total Orders')
ax1.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor=color)


ax2 = ax1.twinx()  
color = 'tab:blue'
ax2.set_ylabel('Online Order Rate', color=color)
ax2.plot(hourly_data.index, hourly_data['Online Order Rate'], color=color, label='Online Order Rate', linestyle='--')
ax2.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor=color)


ax1.legend(loc='upper left')
ax2.legend(loc='upper right')

plt.title('Hourly Orders Distribution and Online Order Rate')

plt.show()

We can observe that the total number of orders typically peaks in the morning and evening. The online ordering rate generally varies with the volume of orders, but there are two points worth noting.

During peak order periods, the online ordering rate decreases, which is consistent with the marketing team's research findings: "During peak times, people are too busy and prefer the convenience of ordering offline." This indicates that there is still room for improvement in the feature. Customers prefer to order online in the early hours of the morning because they do not want to disturb the staff.

Explore the order situation of key customers¶

In [149]:
df_grouped = df.groupby('Customer')['Order type'].agg(
    order_amount='count', 
    online_orders_amount=lambda x: (x == 'online').sum()
).reset_index()

df_grouped['offline_orders_amount'] = df_grouped['order_amount'] - df_grouped['online_orders_amount']
df_grouped['online_rate'] = df_grouped['online_orders_amount'] / df_grouped['order_amount']


df_grouped.sort_values(by='order_amount', ascending=False, inplace=True)


df_grouped['online_rate'] = df_grouped['online_rate'].apply(lambda x: f'{x:.2%}')

df_grouped.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)

# scatter_plot

df_scatter_plot = df_grouped
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.scatter(df_scatter_plot['order_amount'], df_scatter_plot['online_orders_amount'], color='blue', alpha=0.5)
plt.title('Relationship between Total Orders and Online Orders')
plt.xlabel('Total Order Amount')
plt.ylabel('Online Orders Amount')
for i in range(len(df_scatter_plot)):
    plt.annotate(df_scatter_plot.index[i], (df_scatter_plot.iloc[i]['order_amount'], df_scatter_plot.iloc[i]['online_orders_amount']))
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

From this, we can understand that enhancing the online ordering rate of key customers is crucial to improving the overall usage rate of the feature. Here, we need to classify the difficulty of persuading customers based on their usage of the feature, to assign different departments to undertake offline visits, marketing activities, etc., encouraging customers to be more willing to use this feature and provide feedback.

df_ctm = df_grouped

df_ctm['online_rate'] = df_ctm['online_rate'].str.rstrip('%').astype('float') / 100.0

# Those who have never placed an order online are the most difficult customers.
ctm_hard = df_ctm[df_ctm['online_orders_amount']==0]

# Customers who have placed orders online and whose online order rate is greater than 10% are considered easy customers
ctm_easy = df_ctm[(df_ctm['online_orders_amount']>0) & (df_ctm['online_rate']>=0.1)]

ctm_middle = df_ctm[(df_ctm['online_orders_amount']>0) & (df_ctm['online_rate']<0.1)]
